:false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76738","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76738"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 16-year-old female presents with acute onset of shortness of breath, cough and wheeze. She has a medical history of asthma with frequent exacerbations. Her medications list includes salbutamol PRN, fluticasone 250ug BD and two courses of oral prednisolone in the last 12 months.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, her pulse rate is 100/min, respiratory rate is 35/min, blood pressure 125/75mmHg, SpO2 92% on room air, and temperature 36.5\u00b0C. Cardiorespiratory exam reveals that she is using her accessory muscles to breathe.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following accessory muscle(s) are used for inspiration?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Sternocleidomastoids","Internal intercostal muscles","Scalenus inferior","Diaphragm","Muscles of the abdominal wall"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIt is important to have a clear understanding of active inspiration, passive expiration, forced inspiration and forced expiration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDuring active inspiration, the \u003Cstrong\u003Ediaphragm\u003C/strong\u003E contracts to expand the thoracic cavity and draw air in.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDuring forced inspiration, additional muscles as well as the diaphragm are used to expand the thoracic cavity and increase the amount of air breathed in. These include \u003Cstrong\u003Esternocleidomastoid\u003C/strong\u003E, scalene, external intercostal muscles, and pectoralis minor. The \u003Cstrong\u003Escalene\u003C/strong\u003E muscles are anterior, posterior and middle - not \u003Cstrong\u003Einferior\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe sternocleidomastoid muscles contract to elevate the sternum\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe external intercostal muscles contract to pull the ribs superiorly\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDuring passive expiration, the diaphragm relaxes which reduces the volume of the thoracic cavity. This is a passive process (does not require energy expenditure or muscle contraction).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDuring forced expiration, additional muscles contract while the diaphragm relaxes to reduce the volume of the thoracic cavity to a great extent. These include the\u003Cstrong\u003E internal intercostal muscles,\u003C/strong\u003E quadratus lumborum and \u003Cstrong\u003Eabdominal muscles.\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe internal intercostal muscles contract to pull the ribs inferiorly\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EQuadratus lumborum contracts to pull the ribs inferiorly\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe abdominal muscles contract to compress the abdomen and reduce intrathoracic volume\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The accessory muscles of ventilation include the sternocleidomastoid, pectorals, trapezius, external intercostals and the scalenes."],"references":["West J, Luks A. West\u0027s respiratory physiology. 10th ed. Lippincott Williams and Wilkins; 2011. (Chapter 7 - \u0022Mechanics of Breathing\u0022)","Shiraishi M, Higashimoto Y, Sugiya R, Mizusawa H, Takeda Y, Fujita S, Nishiyama O, Kudo S, Kimura T, Fukuda K, Tohda Y. Sternocleidomastoid Muscle Thickness Correlates with Exercise Tolerance in Patients with COPD. Respiration. 2023;102(1):64-73. doi: 10.1159/000527100. Epub 2022 Nov 22. PMID: 36412608; PMCID: PMC9843540.","Hudson AL, Gandevia SC, Butler JE. The effect of lung volume on the co-ordinated recruitment of scalene and sternomastoid muscles in humans. J Physiol. 2007 Oct 1;584(Pt 1):261-70. doi: 10.1113/jphysiol.2007.137240. Epub 2007 Aug 9. PMID: 17690147; PMCID: PMC2277075."]},"r